# Bilingual EPUB Reader — Project Plan & Handoff Spec

> A single self-contained HTML file that opens English EPUBs on your Mac and shows
> English (left) + Chinese (right), side by side. Everything stays on your device.
> Built for one user, by that user. No server, no login, no cost.

---

## 1. The one-paragraph summary (read this first)

I want a **single `index.html` file** I open in my browser. I drag in an `.epub`.
It shows **English on the left, Chinese on the right** in two columns, always both
visible — never hide either language. Chinese is for grabbing the gist fast and
finding the parts worth reading deeply in English. The Chinese comes from **free
Google machine translation** (gist-quality is fine and correct for this purpose).
**Per book**, I choose either *translate-as-I-read* (instant, needs internet) or
*translate-the-whole-book-once-and-save* (wait once, then offline + private).
All data — books, reading position, reading list — lives **only on my device** in
the browser's IndexedDB. My **GitHub repo holds only the tool's code, never a single
book or note.** The look and feel should evoke **Apple Books / Safari Reader**:
clean serif body type, generous whitespace, calm, accessible.

---

## 2. Why this shape (the reasoning, so any AI understands the constraints)

The bilingual-ebook world on GitHub splits into TWO jobs that are almost never
combined: **(A) translating** an EPUB into a bilingual file (CLI/AI tools like
`bilingual_book_maker`, `epub-translator`, `epubtrans`) and **(B) reading** it
side-by-side (`epub.js`, `jorkens`, `tomparys/bilingual-reader`). This tool
deliberately does BOTH inside one browser file, using the free translation endpoint
so there is no API key — which matters because **a static HTML file cannot keep
secrets**, so a key-based design was off the table from the start.

Key constraints that drove the design:
- **"Open file, read, close"** → no server, no app, no build step. Just a file.
- **"Everything private"** → books and notes never leave the device; only the empty
  tool goes on GitHub.
- **"Free translation"** → Google's free web endpoint; no key to hide.
- **"Host on GitHub"** → the repo is the *tool*; the *library* is your Mac.

---

## 3. Locked decisions (do not re-litigate these)

| Decision | Choice | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Input format | **EPUB only** | MOBI is proprietary/binary; converting it in-browser is fragile. Convert MOBI→EPUB in **Calibre** (10 seconds). Tool shows a one-line reminder. |
| Layout | **Two columns: English left, Chinese right** | Matches the original sketch. |
| Translation source | **Free Google translate endpoint** (no key) | Gist-quality is the *correct* tool for "understand fast, then read English deeply." |
| Translation timing | **Per-book choice**: live OR translate-once-and-save | User picks at open time. |
| Storage | **IndexedDB** (not localStorage) | localStorage caps ~5MB; a saved book blows past that. IndexedDB holds many books. |
| Reader engine | **epub.js** + **JSZip** | Standard, battle-tested. Never rebuild this wheel. |
| Privacy | Books + data on device only; GitHub = code only | Both privacy concerns satisfied at once. |
| Build style | Incremental, testable stages | ADHD-friendly: see progress fast, never one giant untestable blob. |

---

## 4. Privacy model (important — this is the whole point)

- The HTML file and any libraries (epub.js, JSZip) are the ONLY things in the GitHub repo.
- When you open a book, it is read **locally** and stored in **your browser's IndexedDB**.
  It never uploads anywhere.
- **One exception to flag honestly:** when translating, the *text of each paragraph*
  is sent to Google's translate endpoint over the internet (the file itself never is).
  Once a book is translated-and-saved, no further network calls happen for it — it's
  fully offline and private after that.
- A `.gitignore` will explicitly block any book or data file from ever being committed,
  as a belt-and-suspenders safeguard.

